And downstairs you will find
Wells Fargo team members working

00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:10.660
in two different pavilions with
a number of fun activities --

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:13.550
that's the Let's Read
America Pavilion as well

00:04:13.550 --> 00:04:14.850
as the Hands-on History Pavilion.

00:04:14.850 --> 00:04:18.080
So I hope you'll take some
time to stop by there.

00:04:18.080 --> 00:04:21.800
But now it's my pleasure to
welcome Mary Louise Kelly

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:24.980
of the National Public Radio
who will now moderate our panel.

00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:26.780
Thank you very much.

00:04:26.780 --> 00:04:30.040
[ Applause ]

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:31.780
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Good morning.

00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:33.810
Can you all hear me?

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:35.110
Excellent.

00:04:35.110 --> 00:04:36.410
That's a good start.

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:39.220
I'm going to lay four dates on you.

00:04:39.220 --> 00:04:45.390 position:56%
John Fitzgerald Kennedy was born 100
years ago this year, May 29, 1917.

00:04:45.390 --> 00:04:51.720
He was married September
12, 1953, elected president,

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:55.270
took the oath of office
January 20, 1961.

00:04:55.270 --> 00:05:03.220
And of course died November 22,
1963 in Dallas at the age of 46.

00:05:03.220 --> 00:05:07.000
And I start with those dates
because they're so well known.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.150
The arc of his life
is so well known.

00:05:09.150 --> 00:05:12.150
So many books have already
been written about him,

00:05:12.150 --> 00:05:17.480
and yet as evidenced by the trio
of authors on stage with us today,

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.570
there is still so much curiosity
about that extraordinary life.

00:05:20.570 --> 00:05:24.500
So it's a privilege to get to kick
off the book festival by talking

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:27.590
about that extraordinary life
for a few minutes with you all

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:32.860
and maybe asking what lessons
from that life might apply

00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:36.780
to today's interesting times.

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:39.360
So welcome to each of
the three of you --

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:43.160
Tom Oliphant, Kathy
McKeon, Steve Levingston.

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:44.460
Welcome to you all.

00:05:44.460 --> 00:05:47.870
I thought we would start by letting
each of you share a little bit

00:05:47.870 --> 00:05:51.960
of the particular vantage
point that you bring

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:53.580
and what grounds your book covers.

00:05:53.580 --> 00:05:56.120
And I know you each brought
a few pictures we can share

00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:59.540
to give you a little bit of a taste
of some of this new literature

00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:02.370
and scholarship coming
out on Kennedy.

00:06:02.370 --> 00:06:05.750
So we're going to go, I guess,
in the order we're seated.

00:06:05.750 --> 00:06:10.560
Tom Oliphant, that means you get
the first word with your book,

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:15.560
The Road to Camelot: Inside
JFK's Five-Year Campaign.

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:20.520
And your book, I know, is about
his rise to the White House

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:22.590
and how close he came to losing.

00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:24.280
So maybe you can tell us
a little bit about that.

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:26.690
I'm going to let you just
briefly talk us through some

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:28.080
of the pictures you
brought to share.

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:32.540
So we'll go to this first one
and just tell us a little bit

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:35.000
about the perspective
that you bring.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.210
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: That
picture is of what they call

00:06:38.210 --> 00:06:41.920
in politics a boiler room.

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:51.310
It's actually the sun porch of Bob
Kennedy's house in Hyannis Port.

00:06:51.310 --> 00:06:52.610
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: OK.

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:53.910
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant:
And it is shortly

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:59.370
after dawn after the election.

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:05.530
Kennedy at that point knows that he
is going to be the president-elect,

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:09.750
but there are still a lot of
states in play and this was one

00:07:09.750 --> 00:07:12.420
of those election nights
that was an all-nighter.

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:17.110
Kennedy didn't go to bed until
around 3:00 for a short nap.

00:07:17.110 --> 00:07:19.180
And in those days, the first sign

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:23.100
that you'd been elected
president was the appearance

00:07:23.100 --> 00:07:24.750
of secret service agents.

00:07:24.750 --> 00:07:26.050
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: A-ha.

00:07:26.050 --> 00:07:27.580
They showed up and you knew
you were in good shape.

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:29.940
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: Around dawn.

00:07:29.940 --> 00:07:35.580
And it was when he woke up
in his house in the compound,

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:38.760
he noticed the agents and
that was the first clue

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:41.560
to him that this had happened.

00:07:41.560 --> 00:07:49.270 position:56%
While he was sleeping -- the last
thing I'll say -- on election night,

00:07:49.270 --> 00:07:55.490
the state that in the public's
mind and in journalism's coverage

00:07:55.490 --> 00:07:59.070
that tipped this thing that made
it pretty clear that he was going

00:07:59.070 --> 00:08:03.090
to be the next president was
Minnesota which went back

00:08:03.090 --> 00:08:09.520
and forth all through the night and
didn't fall over into his column

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:13.120
until shortly before dawn.

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:19.210
And the wise guys in that room
and the one just to the left

00:08:19.210 --> 00:08:24.140
at that point knew that
they had, as one put it,

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:26.110
fallen over the finish line.

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:27.410
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
Ah, OK [laughing].

00:08:27.410 --> 00:08:29.290
Alright. We're going to
quickly flip through a few

00:08:29.290 --> 00:08:30.590
of the others you brought.

00:08:30.590 --> 00:08:33.580
Stop me if you want or just
tell us what we're seeing.

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:34.880
Why'd you pick this one?

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:38.730
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: That's
a look at this guy right

00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:41.890
at the beginning of
the whole process.

00:08:41.890 --> 00:08:46.560
The hour mentor in this kind
of work, Theodore White,

00:08:46.560 --> 00:08:49.810 position:56%
in The Making of the President 1960,

00:08:49.810 --> 00:08:55.120
wrote a story of a
year plus campaign.

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:59.060
What Curtis Wilkie and I
discovered in our research was

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:02.270
that this process was
actually five years

00:09:02.270 --> 00:09:06.290
of conscious pursuit
of national office.

00:09:06.290 --> 00:09:07.590
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: OK.

00:09:07.590 --> 00:09:10.140
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: And it
started in the late summer of 1955

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:12.520
and that's what John
Kennedy looked like then.

00:09:12.520 --> 00:09:16.090
You can still see a trace of
the skinny kid after the war.

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:17.390
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Yeah.

00:09:17.390 --> 00:09:22.200
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: By the end
of 1956 when he made the decision

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:26.840
to actually run for
president, he had filled out.

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:30.590
But that's what he looked
like when this all began.

00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:32.390
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: OK.

00:09:32.390 --> 00:09:36.320
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: Everybody
remembers the rackets committee,

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:38.220
as we called it in journalism.

00:09:38.220 --> 00:09:45.130
It was a senate investigation of
corruption in the labor movement

00:09:45.130 --> 00:09:51.690
that focused primarily
on the Teamsters Union

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:56.790 position:56%
and introduced the country for the
first time to the guy in the middle,

00:09:56.790 --> 00:10:01.030 position:56%
Bob Kennedy, and to the evil figures

00:10:01.030 --> 00:10:04.350
in the Teamsters Union back
then, first a guy named --

00:10:04.350 --> 00:10:05.780
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: So
what's the date on this phot?

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:09.590
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: This would
be in the summer of 1957.

00:10:09.590 --> 00:10:11.190
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: 57.

00:10:11.190 --> 00:10:12.490
Alright.

00:10:12.490 --> 00:10:13.790
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: And
he'd already decided to run.

00:10:13.790 --> 00:10:20.810 position:56%
His principal antagonist on the left
was Eleanor Roosevelt, shown here.

00:10:20.810 --> 00:10:26.800
She nipped at his heels for at
least three years, a little longer.

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:30.970
She didn't trust him and
she didn't like him mostly

00:10:30.970 --> 00:10:35.490
because of his behavior during the
heyday of Senator Joseph McCarthy.

00:10:35.490 --> 00:10:36.790
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Mmhmm.

00:10:36.790 --> 00:10:39.520
&gt;&gt; Thomas Oliphant: But she
changed, as Kennedy did.

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:44.510
And by this moment, when he
was nominated for president,

00:10:44.510 --> 00:10:48.190
you see Sam Rayburn
moderating a -- quote --

00:10:48.190 --> 00:10:53.230
debate which really wasn't much
of one before the Texas delegation

00:10:53.230 --> 00:10:55.500
and a few hangers-on
from Massachusetts

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:59.270
at the Democratic Convention
in Los Angeles.

00:10:59.270 --> 00:11:03.560
Johnson, of course, and
Kennedy are shown there.

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:08.310
This is two days before
he was actually nominated.

00:11:08.310 --> 00:11:09.610
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Alright.

00:11:09.610 --> 00:11:10.910
Thank you so much.

00:11:10.910 --> 00:11:13.840
Kathy, we're going to come to you
and let you give a little preview

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:18.850
of your book, Jackie's Girl: My
Life With the Kennedy Family.

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:20.650
For those of you who
haven't had the chance

00:11:20.650 --> 00:11:27.400 position:56%
to read this delightful book yet, it
is Kathy's story of her time working

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:31.790
for Jacqueline Kennedy and as
her personal assistant living

00:11:31.790 --> 00:11:36.680 position:56%
with the Kennedy family for 13 years
and sometimes nannying to the kids.

00:11:36.680 --> 00:11:38.820
And Jackie's Girl was what
Rose Kennedy called you.

00:11:38.820 --> 00:11:40.120
Is that right?

00:11:40.120 --> 00:11:41.420
&gt;&gt; Kathy McKeon: Yes.

00:11:41.420 --> 00:11:42.720
Yes.

00:11:42.720 --> 00:11:44.020
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: The nickname?

00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:45.320
&gt;&gt; Kathy McKeon: Yes.

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:46.620
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: OK.

00:11:46.620 --> 00:11:47.920
So let's go through your
pictures and you can tell us.

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:50.500
&gt;&gt; Kathy McKeon: This was at
my wedding in '71 and it was

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:53.230
in Astoria Manor in New York.

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:55.880
And I sent John [inaudible]
Jackie, I called Madame,

00:11:55.880 --> 00:11:58.190
an invitation to Mr. Onassis.

00:11:58.190 --> 00:12:01.190
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
Hang on one second.

00:12:01.190 --> 00:12:03.950
Can you all hear Kathy OK?

00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:09.450
Kathy, maybe take your mic and
just hold it a little bit closer

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:12.960
to your mouth so we make sure
we can hear your stories.

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:14.260
&gt;&gt; Kathy McKeon: Like that?

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:15.560
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: You
might need to unpin it.

